canonical:
  title: 祭楚州陣亡將士
  author: 崔致遠
  language: lzh
  text: 爾等尺籍從軍寸心報國羔裘武飾旣以力稱馬革雄圖早將身許爰有徐孽來侵楚封舂喉之壯氣未申失手之寃聲遽起始見荷戈就列飜爲復矢成行然而功其可稱死且不朽有狼瞫之君子無羊斟之小人昔時之重義輕生不求苟活今日之名存身喪豈貯遺悲魂其有知各歆薄酹
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 祭楚州陣亡將士
  author: 崔致遠
  language: lzh
  text: 爾等。尺籍從軍。寸心報國。羔裘武飾。旣以力稱。馬革雄圖。早將身許。爰有徐孽。來侵楚封。舂喉之壯氣未申。失手之寃聲遽起。始見荷戈就列。飜爲復矢成行。然而功其可稱。死且不朽。有狼瞫之君子。無羊斟之小人。昔時之重義輕生。不求苟活。今日之名存身喪。豈貯遺悲。魂其有知。各歆薄酹。
korean:
  title: 초주의 전쟁에 죽은 장사에게 제사 지내다
  author: 최치원
  language: kor
  text: 너희들은 척적(尺籍 병적(兵籍))으로 입대하여 충심으로 나라의 은혜를 갚으려 하였도다. 고구(羔裘 염소 갖옷)로 위엄스럽게 꾸민 것이 힘에 알맞고, 마혁(馬革)의 웅대한 도략은 일찍 몸을 나라에 허락하였도다. 서(徐) 땅의 도둑이 와서 초(楚)나라의 봉강(封疆)을 침노하였을 때, 가슴에 찬 장한 기운을 펴지 못하여 실수의 원성이 문득 일어났도다. 처음에 창을 메고 항오(行伍)에 나아갔다가, 문득 화살에 맞은 시체가 줄을 이루었도다. 그러나 공은 칭찬할 만하게 되었으니 죽어도 썩지 아니하리라. 낭담(狼瞫) 같은 군자는 있고 양짐(羊斟) 같은 소인은 없었도다. 옛날 그 당시에 의(義)를 중히 여기고 생(生)을 가볍게 여겨 구차하게 살려고 하지 아니하였으며, 오늘날에 와서 몸은 죽었어도 이름이 있으니, 슬퍼할 것이 있겠는가. 혼은 알고 있을 테니 각각 박주(薄酒)를 흠양할지어다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1120_010_0030&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: A Sacrifice for the Fallen Soldiers of Cho Province
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: You enlisted by the roster's command, repaying the nation's grace with loyal hearts. Adorned in ceremonial garb befitting warriors, your strength was evident; the great ambitions carried in cavalry charges saw your bodies pledged early to the state. When the bandits from the borderlands came to invade Cho's territories, the fierce courage burning in your breasts could not be unleashed—instead, the cry of defeat rose suddenly. You advanced first with spear in hand through the ranks of soldiers, only to find yourselves fallen in rows, pierced by arrows. Yet your deeds shine bright, and death shall not diminish your names. Among you are gentlemen of wolf-like vigilance, with no cowards of sheep-like counsel. In those days you valued righteousness above life, seeking no shameful survival; now your bodies rest while your names endure—what cause for lamentation remains? Your spirits surely know and comprehend; each of you, receive this humble libation.
  footnotes:
    - The reference to 'wolf-like vigilance' (狼瞫) and 'sheep-like counsel' (羊斟) alludes to contrasting virtues of moral courage and moral weakness in classical Chinese literature.
    - The 'cavalry charges' (馬革) metaphorically references the soldier's aspiration to die honorably in battle, a Confucian ideal.
    - This is a ritual prayer (祭文) composed in the ornate parallel prose style characteristic of Silla's scholarly elite, particularly those influenced by Chinese literary traditions.
